<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910117-0097</DOCNO><DOCID>910117-0097.</DOCID><HL>   Hungary to Receive   Loan of $318 Million   From IMF for Oil Bill</HL><DATE>01/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   EUROP</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)BANKS (BNK)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><GV>INTERNATIONAL AGENCIES AND INSTITUTIONS (INT)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund approved aloan of about $318 million to Hungary to help it cope withhigher oil prices for the 12 months ending this October.   A further $171 million loan may be disbursed, at Hungary'srequest, when data for the first six months of this periodare available, the IMF said.</LP><TEXT>   The IMF is lending money to nations hit particularly hardby the Mideast crisis and the subsequent rise in oil prices.Eastern European nations are particularly affected, as theynow must use hard currency to purchase imported oil and arepaying market prices. Previously, they imported oil from theSoviet Union at subsidized prices.   In addition, the IMF is soon to consider a $1.6 billionthree-year loan agreement with Hungary, financial sourcessaid, with a decision expected in mid-February. In March1990, the IMF lent Hungary $224 million to help itrestructure its economy.</TEXT></DOC>